  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <p xml:id="KT217-kilavi">uṭaṉpōkku nayappat tōḻi talaimakaṭkuk kūṟiyatu. </p>
        <p xml:lang="en">Spoken to HER by the confidante so that [she] would
          yield to going away together. </p>
      </div>

      <div rend="parallel">
        <lg xml:id="KT217">

          <l>tiṉaikiḷi kaṭikeṉiṟ pakalu mollu</l>
          <l>miravunī varutali ṉūṟu mañcuval</l>
          <l>yāṅkuccey vāmem miṭumpai nōykkeṉa</l>
          <l>vāṅkiyāṉ kūṟiya vaṉaittiṟkup piṟitucet</l>
          <l>tōṅkumalai nāṭa ṉuyirttōṉ maṉṟa</l>
          <l>vaitē kāmam yāṉē</l>
          <l>kaḻimutuk kuṟaimaiyum paḻiyumeṉ ṟiciṉē.</l>
        </lg>

        <lg xml:lang="en">

          <l>“If they said: "go chasing parakeets from the millet",</l>
          <l rend="indent6">it would be possible at midday too. <note place="foot">The conditional
            presumably has to be taken as a hypothetical one. This is preferred also by T.V.G. who
            thinks the point is that the field is already harvested, so the lovers cannot meet there
            anymore.</note>
          </l>
          <l>Because of your coming at night, I fear obstacles too.</l>
          <l>What do we do against the pain that afflicts us?”</l>
          <l rend="indent3">When I spoke thus,</l>
          <l>he thought of another [thing to do] in such [a state of affairs], <note place="foot">Is
            there any way to avoid the poetological interpretation here, namely that HE listens to
            the confidante's words and is ready to flee with HER? (So the poem has to be understood
            as a discussion between HIM and the confidante, which, according to the <term xml:lang="ta">kiḷavi</term> , is repeated to HER by the confidante).</note>
          </l>
          <l>the man from the land of high mountains, [and] he sighed indeed:</l>
          <l>“desire is [all very] well!”</l>
          <l rend="indent8">But I,</l>
          <l>I said: “[this is] a very old short-cut, and [it is] blame.”</l>


        </lg>
      </div>
    </body>
  </text>
