<note><term xml:lang="ta">mutukkuṟaimai </term> is a problem. While <term xml:lang="ta">mutu </term>
        is, of course, "old", <term xml:lang="ta">kuṟaimai</term> is not attested otherwise, besides
        in <term xml:base="ta">Kali</term> 62.9 (disputably dependent on the KT passage); one <term xml:lang="ta"> mutukkuṟai</term> is to be found in NA 366.9. Cām. glosses with <term xml:lang="ta">mikka aṟivuṭaimai</term> , "great wisdom" (thus also T.V.G.'s understanding,
        who explains it as <term xml:lang="ta"> mutukku-uṟaimai</term> , which likewise does not
        seem attested). If we take a look at the etymology, <term xml:lang="ta">kuṟaimai </term>
        should or at least could be an abstract noun to <term xml:lang="ta">kuṟai-tal</term> "to
        shorten". If the <term xml:lang="ta">kiḷavi </term> here is applicable, this would make good
        sense: going away together would indeed be the classical short-cut to circumvent further
        family complications.</note>
